      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "*Hmph.* \"Keep it to the math.\" As if the mathematics of debt could ever be truly free of the chaotic, greedy spirit of a goblin raid! But fine, I shall attempt to cage these numbers, though they will inevitably twitch like a startled goblin when I mention the principal.\n\nTo give you precise numbers for Year 5 versus Year 25, I would need your exact initial loan amount, as the payment amount itself is derived from that principal. However, I can give you the *principle* of the shift, which is the mathematical heart of the matter, and it's a shift as dramatic as a goblin suddenly deciding to trade its rusty sword for a slightly shinier pebble.\n\nLet's assume a standard loan structure. In the early years (like Year 5), the interest portion of your payment is significantly higher because the outstanding principal balance is still very large. The interest calculation is based on: **(Remaining Balance) $\\times$ (Annual Interest Rate / 12)**. Because the Remaining Balance is high, the interest chunk is big.\n\nBy Year 25, however, the principal has been whittled down considerably through those earlier payments. The Remaining Balance is much smaller",
